AGI - Fatah launched an appeal to Hamas, exhorting him to leave power in Gaza to safeguard "the existence of Palestinians" in the Strip, where Israel intensified military operations after breaking the truce last Tuesday, already making several hundred deaths among the Palestinian population. Mounther al-Hayek, spokesman of the party of the President of the Palestinian National Authority (Anp), Abu Mazen in a message delivered by the coastal enclave.
&nbsp;
"Hamas must show compassion for Gaza, his children, his women and his men," he said, inviting the Islamist movement "to leave the government." The Palestinian militant group must "be fully aware that the imminent battle will lead to the end of the Palestinian existence" in the Strip if he decides to remain in power, warned Hayek, warning "difficult, hard and painful days awaiting the inhabitants of Gaza".
&nbsp;
Hamas took power in Gaza in 2007, extruding the Anp dominated by Fatah after bloody clashes. Since then, there have been no elections in the Strip and the numerous attempts to reconcile Palestinian factions have failed. On October 7, 2023, Hamas launched a massive attack on Israel, killing over 1,200 people and seizing about 250 people. The Jewish state responded with a very hard war that in 17 months it cost almost 50 thousand Palestinians, according to the Islamic movement.
&nbsp;
On 19 January, thanks to the mediation of Egypt, Qatar and the US, with the decisive pressure of the American president entering Donald Trump, a ceasefire came into force that provided three stages. After a first 42-day period, in which 33 hostages were released and over 1,700 Palestinian prisoners, efforts to find an agreement to continue failed.
&nbsp;
The positions were distant: Hamas pressed for the start of negotiations on the second stage - as provided for in the agreement - focused on the definitive cessation of war and the withdrawal of Israeli troops from the Strip, in exchange for the return of all the kidnapped.
&nbsp;
For his part, Netanyahu aimed at a continuation of the first phase, with the further release of hostages in exchange for Palestinian prisoners, but without the conclusion of the conflict or the withdrawal of soldiers, conditions that risked dropping his executive for the harsh opposition of the extreme right. On Tuesday, Israel accused Hamas of rejecting all the proposals put on the table and broke the truce, recovering military operations in the Strip.
&nbsp;
Yesterday, Israeli Defence Minister Israel Katz threatened to annex parts of Gaza unless Hamas frees all 58 prisoners, of which 34 are believed to have died. Last December, during talks in Cairo, Hamas and Fatah agreed to create a committee of 10-15 politically independent technocrats, most of which from Gaza, to jointly manage the Strip.
&nbsp;
Two months later, US President, Donald Trump, presented a plan for the future of Gaza which provides for the forced displacement of the Palestinian population for a reconstruction of the 'Riviera' style of luxury.
&nbsp;
A harsh view from the Arab leaders of the region who at the beginning of March approved an alternative plan that would see Hamas cut off from the management of the enclave in favor of a committee of independent Palestinian technocrats, in view of the return of the Ap in the territory. Israel, which aims to eradicate the Islamist group from the coastal enclave, but which is also contrary to the management of power by the authorities of Ramallah, rejected the project.&nbsp;
